title.narrative: INFANT YOUNG CHILD AND ADOLESCENT NUTRITION

description.narrative: Increased quality of relevant key nutrition services for infants, children and adolescents especially in the most vulnerable governorates and in humanitarian situations., which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition In Early Childhood (Covid), Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024, all newborns, children, adolescents and women in Iraq access and equitably use affordable, high-impact health and nutrition services, especially the most vulnerable in humanitarian situations.

title.narrative: Increased quality of relevant key nutrition services for infants, children and adolescents especially in the most vulnerablegovernorates and in humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: Despite the limited funding outside humanitarian contexts, UNICEF made considerable progress to increase the quality of nutrition services for infants, children, and adolescents, especially through policy, advocacy, and capacity-building. UNICEF supported the Ministry of Health to develop an adolescent nutrition guideline and contributed to the development of the first national guideline on Early Childhood Development led by the Ministry of Education, including components on appropriate Infant and Young Child Feeding (IYCF). UNICEF also funded training of 1,170 health personnel as well as printing and distribution of 100,000 communication materials on,inter alia, IYCF practice and micronutrient deficiency prevention and management. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/01/2022
